<p>I finally found how to construct metadata for a PNG image using the C# class:</p>  <pre><code>System.Windows.Media.Imaging.BitmapMetadata; </code></pre>  <p>which is achieved by:</p>  <pre><code>BitmapMetadata metadata = new BitmapMetadata("png"); metadata.SetQuery("/[0]tEXt/Keyword1", "Associated Text"); metadata.SetQuery("/[1]tEXt/Second Keyword", "New Text"); metadata.SetQuery("/[2]tEXt/Key3", "More Text");  BitmapFrame frame = BitmapFrame.Create(someBitmapSource, null, metadata, null);  var encoder = new PngBitmapEncoder(); encoder.Frames.Clear(); encoder.Frames.Add(frame);  using (FileStream fs = new FileStream(someFilePath, FileMode.Create)) {     encoder.Save(fs); } </code></pre>  <p>But certain keywords such as <em>GPS</em> and <em>PNG</em> cause</p>  <p><em>ArgumentException was unhandled error: Property cannot be found.</em></p>  <p>I believe this is caused by BitmapMetadata being generic for a range of image types, but is there a way to still use these keywords? Or at the very least a list of keywords that are restricted by BitmapMetadata?</p>